High-Ca boninites from the active Tonga Arc

Lauren B. Cooper, 
Terry Plank, 
Richard J. Arculus, 
Erik H. Hauri, 
Paul S. Hall, 
Stephen W. Parman, 
First published: 15 October 2010
https://doi.org/10.1029/2009JB006367
Citations: 90
Sections
PDF

Abstract

[1] We report the first known occurrence of high-Ca boninites within an active submarine island arc, at Volcano A within the Tonga Arc. Both the whole rock and a population of melt inclusions (in Fo86–92 olivines) from a dredged satellite cone have compositions classified as high-Ca boninite. All samples from Volcano A, however, may be related to parental boninites, given the similarity in their rare earth element patterns and their coherency along a similar liquid line of descent. The primary high-Ca boninite liquids were generated in the mantle wedge by high cumulative degrees of melting (>∼24%) at typical mantle wedge temperatures (<1300°C) driven by an influx of slab-derived fluid (>4 wt % H2O in primary liquids). We propose a two-stage model for generating primary boninite liquids at Volcano A: (1) melting of fertile peridotite within the Lau back-arc basin, followed by (2) remelting of this residual peridotite with slab-derived fluid beneath the Tonga Arc. The occurrence of high-Ca boninites at Volcano A is related to the relative location and duration of back-arc spreading. Here, the Eastern Lau Spreading Center has been processing mantle for ∼1 Ma, and corner flow circulation brings mantle from the back-arc melting regime into the arc melting regime at a rate that is a significant fraction (>30%) of the convergence rate. On the basis of Si6.0 and Ti6.0 relationships, we argue that a significant portion of the central Tonga Arc near Volcano A, as well as several other arc volcanoes with active back-arc basins, are also erupting basaltic andesites with boninite parentage.

1. Introduction

[2] Boninites are volcanic rocks of unusual compositions [Petersen, 1890], with high SiO2 (>52 wt %), high MgO (>8 wt %), and low TiO2 (<0.5 wt %) [Le Bas, 2000]. Boninites are mostly found in subduction zone fore arcs and trench slopes predominantly in the south and western Pacific, and within ophiolites [Crawford et al., 1989]. The age of the boninites at the type locality of Chichijima and those recovered northward from this island along the strike of the present-day Izu-Bonin fore arc by Ocean Drilling Program (ODP) Leg 125 is 50 to 45 Ma [Cosca et al., 1998]. Concurrent formation of various boninite types along the length of the Izu-Bonin-Mariana system was coincident with arc inception [Pearce et al., 1992; Stern and Bloomer, 1992; Cosca et al., 1998].

[3] Boninites are divided into two broad subtypes, high-Ca (CaO/Al2O3 > 0.75) and low-Ca (CaO/Al2O3 < 0.75; consistent with the type Chichijima boninite), each of which require different conditions of formation [Crawford et al., 1989]. In general, boninite generation is thought to require the melting of refractory mantle (i.e., low modal clinopyroxene (cpx); cpx-poor lherzolite or harzburgite) fluxed by hydrous fluid [Crawford et al., 1989], although there is a disagreement as to whether elevated mantle temperatures (>1450°C) are required [Falloon and Danyushevsky, 2000] or not [Tatsumi, 1981; Umino and Kushiro, 1989; van der Laan et al., 1989; Kushiro, 1990]. Generation of high-Ca boninites is favored by the melting of a source initially less refractory (i.e., higher modal cpx; cpx-poor lherzolite) than the harzburgite source needed to produce low-Ca boninites [Crawford et al., 1989]. Although the initial mantle sources of the boninite subtypes may vary, at the conclusion of mantle melting, the primary liquids of each subtype must be in equilibrium with an olivine + orthopyroxene (opx) residue (i.e., harzburgite) [Crawford et al., 1989]. Due to the unique conditions postulated for boninite generation, models for its petrogenesis often invoke unusual tectonic settings such as subduction zone initiation [Pearce et al., 1992; Stern and Bloomer, 1992; Escuder Viruete et al., 2006], back-arc initiation [Crawford et al., 1981; Kincaid and Hall, 2003], mid-ocean ridge subduction [Monzier et al., 1993], slab rollback [Bédard, 1999], and mantle plume-arc interaction [Falloon et al., 2007].

[4] Here, we report the discovery of high-Ca boninite and related magmas erupted from Volcano A, a hydrothermally active submarine volcano on the volcanic front of the active Tonga (Tofua) Arc (R. J. Arculus, Voyage Summary SS11/2004: NoToVE-2004 (Northern Tonga Vents Expedition) Submarine hydrothermal plume activity and petrology of the northern Tofua Arc, Tonga, 2004, available at http://www.marine.csiro.au/nationalfacility/voyagedocs/2004/Summary_SS11_2004.pdf). This finding is significant because it represents the only active volcano in which a boninitic suite (i.e., eruptives derived from a parental boninite liquid) has been discovered and is the first boninitic suite reported from a normal arc segment. Johnson et al. [1983] reported a single high-Ca boninite lava flow on Bamus Volcano in the New Britain Arc, apparently unrelated to other eruptives at this location. The appearance of high-Ca boninitic volcanism within a mature intra-oceanic island arc also implies that extraordinary tectonic settings are unnecessary to explain the genesis of some boninites.

[5] In this paper, we present major element, trace element, and volatile data for whole rocks, volcanic glasses, phenocrysts, and olivine-hosted melt inclusions from Volcano A, and consider how high-Ca boninite primary liquids from this volcano are generated in the mantle wedge. We pose the following questions: How are these boninites related to magmas erupting along the rest of the Tonga Arc? What is the key ingredient for boninite generation in this portion of the Tonga Arc? And, what are the relative roles of slab-derived fluid, mantle temperature, and prior melting within the Lau back-arc basin in the generation of these arc boninites?

2. Geological Setting and Sampling

[6] The Tonga Arc is a volcanic chain dominated by submarine edifices in the southern Pacific, sandwiched between the hot spot-related Samoan islands to the north and the Kermadec Volcanic Arc to the south (Figures 1a and 1b). Volcanism within the Tonga Arc results from the westward subduction of the Pacific Plate at the Tonga Trench, beneath the Australian Plate and several microplates of the Lau back-arc basin [Zellmer and Taylor, 2001]. Rapid extension within the Lau Basin results in many spreading ridges, located at various distances to the arc. The combination of extension within the Lau Basin and subduction at the Tonga Trench leads to convergence rates which increase northward to a maximum of 240 mm/yr, the highest in the world [Bevis et al., 1995].

[7] Volcano A is a totally submarine volcano located within the central portion of the Tonga Arc, east of the Eastern Lau Spreading Center (ELSC) at ∼21°S (Figure 1b). At this latitude, the full back-arc spreading rate at the ELSC is ∼77 mm/yr and the convergence rate at the Tonga Trench is ∼165 mm/yr, moderate values within the Tonga-Lau system [Zellmer and Taylor, 2001; Bevis et al., 1995]. Volcano A is ∼30 km southwest of the Tonga Arc island group of Hunga-Ha'apai, which erupted as recently as March 2009 (as reported in the Smithsonian Institution Global Volcanism Program database). Multibeam sonar mapping of Volcano A, during the SS11/2004 Research Voyage of the Australian Marine National Facility (Northern Tonga Vents Expedition (NoToVE)) in November 2004, revealed two cones (R. J. Arculus, Voyage Summary SS11/2004: NoToVE-2004 (Northern Tonga Vents Expedition) Submarine hydrothermal plume activity and petrology of the northern Tofua Arc, Tonga, 2004, available at http://www.marine.csiro.au/nationalfacility/voyagedocs/2004/Summary_SS11_2004.pdf) (Figure 1c). The pristine southern cone (∼10 km in diameter; summit <100 m below sea level (mbsl)) is linked to the cratered and faulted northern cone (∼6 km in diameter; summit <700 mbsl) by a SSE/NNW striking lineament of satellite cones. There is an active hydrothermal system on this volcanic complex, consistent with extreme enrichments in platinum group elements and Au within the lavas [Mungall et al., 2008]. This, coupled with the relatively unaltered morphology of the cones and glassy dredge samples lacking Mn coatings, indicates that Volcano A was formed by relatively recent volcanism.

[8] Five locations on Volcano A were dredged during the NoToVE (Figure 1c). A dredge on a satellite cone north of the northern cone at ∼1,650 mbsl recovered the high-Ca boninite sample (dredge ND-04; sample LC-A-4). High-Ca boninite whole rock compositions have also been reported by Karrei [2008] for samples from dredges ND-01, ND-02, ND-03, and ND-04. In this paper, we argue that all samples from Volcano A are petrologically related and together constitute a single boninitic volcanic complex.

[9] High-Ca boninites within the Tonga-Lau system are not limited to Volcano A, but are also present near the northern terminations of the Tonga Ridge and the Lau Basin [Falloon et al., 1989; Falloon and Crawford, 1991; Sobolev and Danyushevsky, 1994; Danyushevsky et al., 1995; Falloon and Danyushevsky, 2000; Falloon et al., 2007; Falloon et al., 2008] (Figure 1b). In this region, the tectonic setting is more complex: the Pacific-Australian Plate boundary transitions from convergent to transform, possibly permitting Samoan mantle to leak into the Tonga-Lau mantle through a slab window [Millen and Hamburger, 1998; Turner and Hawkesworth, 1998; Smith et al., 2001; Keller et al., 2008]. The North Tonga boninites are found in two submarine settings: an eastern group (1.4–3.1 Ma), sampled within a prominent graben that cuts the northern extension of the Tonga Arc; and a western group (580–890 ka), located on young volcanic cones associated with northern Lau Basin rifts [Falloon et al., 2007]. Thus, it appears that the North Tonga boninites are associated with either an older episode of arc volcanism (1.4–3.1 Ma) or younger back-arc rifting (<1 Ma). In May 2009, a possible boninitic eruption was confirmed at West Mata Volcano, a submarine cone within the western group [Michael et al., 2009; J. Resing et al., Northeast Lau Response Cruise (NELRC), 2009, available at http://oceanexplorer.noaa.gov/explorations/09laubasin/background/NELRC_CruiseReport_final.pdf). Geochemical and experimental studies of the North Tonga boninites indicate equilibration at relatively shallow mantle depths (∼45 km; 15 kbar) and elevated temperatures (up to 1480°C), for magmas with primary H2O contents up to 2 wt % [Falloon and Danyushevsky, 2000; Sobolev and Danyushevsky, 1994].

[10] We have studied whole rocks (WRs), volcanic glasses, phenocrysts, and melt inclusions from Volcano A in order to provide chemical compositions and volatile contents of the high-Ca boninite liquids. Previous studies aimed at measuring the volatile contents of submarine lavas have focused on glass rinds; however, at such shallow water depths as Volcano A (∼100–2,000 mbsl; ∼10–200 bar), major loss of H2O to vapor will occur upon eruption for any magmatic liquid containing more than ∼0.3 to 1.4 wt % H2O with depth, which are concentrations expected for arc magmas [Newman et al., 2000]. To circumvent this problem, we focused on the analysis of melt inclusions (MIs), pockets of melt trapped within a phenocryst at pressure, which may preserve undegased magmatic H2O contents [Anderson, 1979; Sobolev and Chaussidon, 1996] (see Wallace [2005] for a comprehensive review of MIs). Lavas erupted from submarine volcanoes, such as Volcano A, quench in contact with cold seawater, forming glassy MIs which may have undergone minimal diffusive loss of H or daughter crystallization. If MIs are trapped in early crystallizing phases, such as olivine, their compositions may directly relate to near-primary liquid compositions, which may record conditions of melting within the mantle wedge.

3. Methods

[11] Samples were crushed, sieved, and hand-picked under a microscope to select fresh phenocrysts, glass, and MIs (see Table 1 for details). Only MIs greater than ∼30 μm in diameter and exhibiting no evidence of daughter crystals, oxides, devitrification, or alteration were selected for analysis. We analyzed only naturally quenched MIs, without rehomogenization by reheating. Such suitable MIs were identified at Volcano A only within high-Ca boninite sample LC-A-4 from dredge ND-04, a flow sample ∼10 cm in diameter, of which ∼20 g of the outer ∼2 cm were studied, including a ∼0.5 cm thick glass rind. This sample yielded ∼30 MI-bearing phenocrysts, mostly within the 250 to 500 μm size fraction and predominantly olivine. In samples from the other dredges, MIs either contained daughter crystals or the phenocrysts were encased in glass, making it difficult to locate viable MIs.

[12] MIs, glasses, and phenocrysts were analyzed for major elements, S, and Cl via electron microprobe (EMP) at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and the American Museum of Natural History (AMNH) (Tables 1 and 2 and Table S1 in the auxiliary material), following the methods reported by Wade et al. [2006]. For the MIs and glasses, check standards were analyzed in each of the five EMP sessions in order to correct for intersession and interlab variability. In almost all sessions, major elements were normalized to check standard FR:ND-70-01 (Fonualei Rift basaltic glass; values reported herein, Table 1, from an AMNH session), and S and Cl were normalized to standards NIST610 (560 ppm S [Ihinger et al., 1994]) and KE12 (3300 ppm Cl [Devine et al., 1995]). Replicate analyses of five MIs and two glass populations yielded average relative standard deviations (standard deviation/average; RSDs) of 5% for major elements (excluding MgO and P2O5; both >20%, due to low concentrations), 10% for Cl, and 26% for S (12% for MIs and 56% for glasses, indicating S heterogeneity within the glasses). The average accuracy for six replicate analyses of Juan de Fuca Ridge (JDF) basaltic glass was 3% relative for all major elements, with the exception of MnO and P2O5 (both >10%).

[13] Volatiles (H2O, CO2, S, Cl, and F) were measured during two sessions at the Carnegie Institution of Washington, using the 6f Cameca ion microprobe via secondary ion mass spectrometry (SIMS) (Table 1). Methods followed those of Hauri [2002], using a basaltic glass calibration curve and in almost all cases measuring H2O as 16O1H. Replicate analyses of four MIs yielded average RSDs of 8% (for H2O, CO2, and F), 4% (for S), and 7% (for Cl). The SIMS and EMP values for S and Cl agree within 10% relative on average, as do the H2O measurements when the SIMS values are compared to those calculated by difference from 100% of the EMP totals. The EMP values are usually shifted toward low S, high Cl, and high H2O relative to SIMS. Taking into account the most consistent intersession calibrations and intrasession precision, we use S and H2O by SIMS throughout the following discussion and diagrams.

[15] Trace element concentrations in glasses and MIs were acquired by laser ablation-ICP-MS (Table 3). Glasses were analyzed at Boston University using a Merchantek/VG Microprobe II 213 nm Nd-YAG laser ablation system coupled to a VG PQ ExCell quadrupole ICP-MS. Samples were ablated in a He–Ar mixture at a flow rate of 0.9 mL/min for both Ar and He. The laser was operated in spot-drill mode using a 10 Hz repetition rate, at 75% power (∼1.2 mJ/pulse), for an energy density of ∼2.4 J/cm2. The beam expander (collimator) was set to 0% and the iris was set to 45%, resulting in a spot size of ∼250 μm. The dwell time for all elements was 10 ms. The laser data were acquired in time-resolved mode and calibrated against USGS glasses BHVO-2g, BIR-1g, and BCR-2g (using the values of Kelley et al. [2003]), with 49Ti as the internal standard. The average precision and accuracy for two replicate analyses of BCR-2 g was 4% RSD and 3% relative, respectively, for all elements.

[16] MIs were analyzed at the Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory of Columbia University using a New Wave UP193-FX laser ablation system coupled to a VG PQ ExCell quadrupole ICP-MS. Samples were ablated in a He–Ar mixture at a flow rate of 0.6 mL/min for Ar and 1.6 mL/min for He. The laser was operated in spot-drill mode (50–100 μm spot size) at 10 Hz, and at 70% power, for an energy density of ∼10.6 to 11.5 J/cm2. The dwell time for all elements was 10 ms. The laser data were acquired in time-resolved mode and calibrated against USGS glasses BHVO-2g and BIR-1g, with 43Ca as the internal standard. The average precision for six replicate analyses of BIR-1g was 12% RSD for all elements, with the exception of Rb, Cs, and U (all >35%); the average accuracy was 5% relative, with the exception of Cs and U (both >50%). The small sizes of the MIs and the extremely low TE concentrations of the Volcano A magmas presented a challenge to the technique.

[17] Olivine phenocrysts were rastered rim-to-rim by LA-ICP-MS (Figure 3b and Figure S1 in the auxiliary material) at 10 Hz, at 50% power (∼0.2 mJ/pulse), and at 3 μm/s, resulting in an ablated trench ∼10 μm in width. Forsterite contents were calculated from the measured Mg/Fe ratio, calibrated using USGS glass BIR-1g and corrected to San Carlos olivine. The precision and accuracy of forsterite for 12 replicate analyses of San Carlos olivine were less than 1% RSD and 0.68% relative (biased to low forsterite), respectively.

[18] Most MIs experience some amount of postentrapment sidewall crystallization, which, in the case of olivine-hosted MIs, can be corrected by adding olivine to MI compositions until equilibrium is achieved with the host lying immediately adjacent to the MI [Sisson and Layne, 1993; Danyushevsky et al., 2000]. In carrying out this calculation, we used a compositionally dependent partition coefficient (KD) for Fe/Mg olivine-liquid exchange [Tamura et al., 2000], and added equilibrium olivine in 0.1% increments. Based on the minimum quantity of Fe3+ required to achieve equilibrium for some olivine-hosted MIs from sample LC-A-4, all Volcano A WR, glass, and MI compositions include 20% Fe3+/ΣFe. This is consistent with what Keller et al. [2008] estimated for the nearby Fonualei Spreading Center, using the same method for volcanic glasses and what Karrei [2008] calculated for other samples from Volcano A (including a different sample from dredge ND-04), using a wet chemistry technique for WRs.

4. Results

4.1. Major and Trace Element Compositions of Whole Rocks, Glasses, Phenocrysts, and Melt Inclusions

[19] We analyzed lava samples recovered from four dredges from Volcano A (ND-01, ND-02, ND-04, and ND-05) (Figure 1c). The high-Ca boninite sample is LC-A-4 from dredge ND-04. Petrographically, this sample is largely aphyric (<1% phenocrysts and 66% groundmass; only 4 olivine phenocrysts encountered in thin section) and contains abundant vesicles (34%) (modal analysis based on 500 points). While the only common phenocryst in the sample is olivine (uncharacteristically clear in color), we found a few rare grains of other phenocryst phases, including cpx, a single opx (Mg # = 74–76), and plagioclase. The groundmass is composed of olivine, cpx, opx, and plagioclase microphenocrysts (<250 μm). Glassy, brown MIs are included in olivine phenocrysts and a single opx phenocryst. The outer ∼1 cm glass rind of this sample and the glass adhering to the phenocrysts both contain abundant microlites. Because these two glass populations yield RSDs of 11% on average for all major elements, we consider them to be a single population and refer to them collectively as glass for the remainder of this paper (Table 2). Samples collected from the other Volcano A dredges contain varying proportions of olivine, cpx, opx, and plagioclase phenocrysts. None of the Volcano A samples contain clinoenstatite, which is characteristic of low-Ca boninites [Crawford et al., 1989].

[20] The largely aphyric WR from sample LC-A-4 is indisputably a boninite according to the IUGS definition, given its high MgO (10.6 wt %; normalized to 100% anhydrous), high SiO2 (54.4 wt %), and low TiO2 (0.36 wt %) [Le Bas, 2000] (Table 2 and Figure 2). Furthermore, it is considered a high-Ca boninite due to its high CaO/Al2O3 (0.85) [Crawford et al., 1989]. On the other hand, the glass from this same sample has less MgO (6.52 wt %) and would be classified as a basaltic andesite, not a boninite. Since the glass was clearly a liquid (although microlite crystallization may have affected the local composition measured by the EMP), this raises the question of whether the WR represents a true high-Ca boninite liquid, or instead reflects crystal accumulation or alteration processes.

[21] The zonation styles and dominant compositions of the olivine population bear on the question of crystallization versus accumulation processes within the high-Ca boninite WR liquid. Making the same assumptions of KD and Fe3+ as above, the WR and glass are in equilibrium with Fo89 and Fo84 olivine, respectively (Table 2). This range of olivine compositions is nearly the same as that observed within the sample (Fo92–85 for ∼40 analyzed olivines) (Table S1 and Figures 3 and S1). In detail, the olivines show different zonation patterns, and so are not consistent with simple fractional crystallization of a single magma. Nonetheless, over 80% of the olivines contain cores with a limited range of compositions (Fo88–89) and a ∼10 μm rim with a limited range of more evolved compositions (Fo85–88), consistent with overall evolution from the WR liquid to the glass liquid. Within this overall evolution, roughly half of the olivine population includes a ∼200 μm mantle that indicates recharge with a more primitive magma in equilibrium with Fo89–91, possibly just prior to eruption. Thus the WR composition may reflect some limited amount of magma mixing and antecryst entrainment, but the olivines clearly record the presence prior to eruption of a magma at least as mafic as the high-Ca boninite WR (crystallizing Fo90–91) evolving to one similar to the basaltic-andesite glass (crystallizing Fo85–87), supporting the existence of both as related magmatic liquids.

[22] Whatever multiple liquids may have mixed to form the high-Ca boninite WR must themselves be related largely by olivine crystallization of a similar parent, since the WR and glass lie close to an olivine control line (Figure 2). Indeed, the glass can be derived from the WR by subtracting ∼11% olivine, the predominant phenocryst. Such olivine subtraction creates a composition that agrees with the glass for all major elements within 5% relative on average, which is within the combined analytical uncertainty of the EMP analyses of the glass and the ICP-ES analyses of the WR. Thus, the glass liquid could have been derived from the high-Ca boninite WR composition simply by olivine (mostly microlite) crystallization.

[23] Further evidence for the existence of high-Ca boninite liquids subject to olivine crystallization comes from the compositions of the olivine-hosted MIs (Table 1). As shown in Figure 2, most of the MI population (14 out of 18 MIs) lies in the boninite field. This, combined with the MIs having CaO/Al2O3 > 0.75, supports the existence of other high-Ca boninite liquids within Volcano A. As a group, the MIs scatter about the same olivine control line that links the WR and glass compositions, and also extend it to higher MgO than the WR, consistent with the presence of a more mafic liquid than the WR, as recorded in the Fo90–91 mantle within the olivine phenocrysts (Figure 3). The olivine compositions adjacent to the MIs include the same range (Fo85–92) and mean (Fo88) as the olivine population as a whole. The MI with the most similar MgO as the WR (ol1-MIa) has a major element composition that is identical (average RSD of 5%) to the WR for all of the major species. In addition, LA-ICP-MS analyses of some of the larger MIs (>50 μm) reveal overall trace element patterns similar to the WR and glass (not shown), and identical trace element ratios as the WR for those elements best determined (e.g., Zr/Y, within 1% relative) (Table 3). Thus, we infer that the MIs also provide direct samples of the high-Ca boninite liquids at Volcano A.

[24] While the MI population is consistent with the WR and glass liquids and their relationship through olivine crystallization, it is important to note that such a conclusion is drawn only from the olivine-corrected MI compositions. As discussed above, most raw MI compositions worldwide are affected by postentrapment sidewall crystallization, and require the addition of equilibrium olivine to reconstitute their original trapped compositions. The Volcano A MIs are no exception, and require 1 to 15% olivine addition (Table 1). Without reconstitution, most of the MIs lie in the basaltic andesite field, far from the host WR. The MIs with the least amount of olivine addition (2 to 9%; Fo85–88 hosts) lie within the boninite and basaltic andesite fields and are more evolved than the WR (Figure 2). The MIs with greater amounts of olivine addition (10 to 15%; Fo85–92 hosts) lie wholly in the boninite field, and include compositions both more evolved and more primitive than the WR. Thus, there is a strong relationship between the amount of MgO in the reconstructed MI, and the amount of olivine added, although this is also a function of the host Fo content, as would be expected. The only MIs that lie in the boninite field in their uncorrected state are somewhat anomalous relative to the other MIs, and contain high CaO/Al2O3 (>1.3), high CaO (>14 wt %), and low TiO2 (<0.3 wt %). These MIs are similar to other “high-Ca” MIs described by Schiano et al. [2000] and are related to the least corrected MIs by ∼25% cpx addition, consistent with dissolution reactions that may occur in magma mush zones [Bédard et al., 2000; Danyushevsky et al., 2004]. The low Al2O3 and unremarkable MgO contents of these MIs limit the extent of plagioclase or olivine assimilation during this process; cpx was the main assimilant, possibly because olivine was already on the liquidus and plagioclase crystallization was suppressed by the high H2O contents (see section 4.2). Although we do not believe that the olivine addition calculation has generated compositional artifacts in the data, mainly because the reconstructed MIs are more consistent with the WR and glass compositions than the unreconstructed ones, we nonetheless retain distinct data symbols on all the plots for MIs with ≤7% olivine addition, those with ≥11%, and those with high CaO/Al2O3.

[25] The other dredges from Volcano A yield WR and glass rind compositions that have lower MgO than boninites (i.e., <8 wt %), and are classified as basaltic andesites (Table 2 and Figure 2). Nonetheless, these compositions can be related to the LC-A-4 high-Ca boninite WR by fractionation of the observed phases (olivine, cpx, opx, and plagioclase). Further evidence for a common heritage between the LC-A-4 high-Ca boninite and the other samples from Volcano A comes from their subparallel rare earth element (REE) patterns, which rise with decreasing Mg #, consistent with crystal fractionation of a common parent (Figure 4). In detail, the LC-A-4 and LC-A-1 WRs have parallel REE patterns, while comparatively the LC-A-5 WR has a higher light REE (LREE) to heavy REE (HREE) ratio, indicating fractionation of cpx. We propose that the entire Volcano A complex is an active high-Ca boninite arc volcano, fed by a high-Ca boninite parent with a near-primary liquid composition (dredge ND-04), which erupts together with its differentiates (the other dredges).

[26] Although the REE patterns support a common heritage for all Volcano A WRs, the shape of the markedly LREE-depleted patterns is in contrast to the U-shaped REE patterns of the type low-Ca Chichijima boninites (Figure 4). U-shaped patterns may be formed by source REE depletion due to melt extraction, followed by LREE addition from a slab-derived fluid or melt [Hickey and Frey, 1982; Coish, 1989]. The extent of LREE enrichment, however, varies widely within the spectrum of both boninite and arc magmas, from LREE-depleted patterns similar to those of mid-ocean ridge basalts to strongly LREE-enriched patterns [Hickey and Frey, 1982; Elliott, 2003]. Thus, while the U-shaped REE pattern (and large ion lithophile element (LILE) patterns in general) may be diagnostic of some boninites, it is not a common feature to all. Specifically, LREE-depleted high-Ca boninites are also found in North Tonga [Falloon et al., 2007] and the Marianas [Hickey and Frey, 1982; Crawford et al., 1986], and may reflect the refractory nature of the mantle and/or a minimal subducted sediment contribution. We propose that REE patterns of boninites are controlled by the same local conditions that generate REE patterns of the arc. In this case, LREE depletion, in addition to Nb and Ta depletions (due to melt extraction) and LILE enrichments (due to fluid-fluxed melting), with respect to REEs and high field strength elements (HFSEs), are common to Tonga Arc magmas [Ewart and Hawkesworth, 1987] and this related high-Ca boninite (Table 3 and Figure 4).

4.2. Volatile Contents of Melt Inclusions

[27] The MIs, which were trapped at depth inside olivines, record preeruptive volatile contents of the Volcano A high-Ca boninite liquid. The least degassed MIs contain >4 wt % H2O, which is within the global arc spectrum (Table 1 and Figure 5) [Wallace, 2005]. In detail, the MIs vary considerably in their volatile content, showing a pattern of decreasing H2O with decreasing S, as is expected from magmatic degassing upon ascent [Sisson and Layne, 1993; Wallace, 2005]. A similar H2O-CO2 degassing trend is not evident, perhaps due to the low CO2 in the MIs (<45 ppm). As such, even the least degassed H2O contents may be minima. Cl varies from 410 to 865 ppm, and roughly follows S and CO2, while F (∼80–170 ppm) correlates inversely with S. The single opx-hosted dacitic MI has very high Cl (>3000 ppm) and F (∼400 ppm), consistent with extensive crystal fractionation required to create this evolved composition.

[28] The degassing process may be modeled using the approach of Sisson and Layne [1993], in which a vapor/melt partition coefficient for S of 55 provides an adequate fit to the Volcano A data (Figure 5). Such a partition coefficient is similar to that estimated for Arenal MIs [Wade et al., 2006], which record similar pressures of MI entrapment (≤2 kbar; see section 4.3). While there is no simple relationship between H2O in the MIs and the forsterite composition of the olivine hosts (Figure 5), possibly reflecting crystallization driven by magmatic cooling rather than degassing, the highest H2O and S contents are recorded near high forsterite domains (Fo88–92). Thus, MIs trapped within the most primitive olivine hosts suggests that H2O contents in the primary high-Ca boninite liquid at Volcano A were >4 wt %.

4.3. Pressure and Temperature Conditions of Entrapped Liquids

[29] The entrapment pressures and temperatures of the Volcano A high-Ca boninitic MIs can be estimated from their H2O-CO2 content on the one hand (using the H2O-CO2-melt solution model of Newman and Lowenstern [2002] for pressure) and their major element compositions on the other (using the olivine-liquid thermometer of Sugawara [2000], which includes the effect of H2O on liquidus depression from Médard and Grove [2008]). On the whole, MIs from Volcano A record shallow entrapment (<2 kbar or <∼7 km depth in the crust) and magmatic temperatures of 1100 to 1200°C, with the exception of the opx-hosted dacitic MI, which records a cooler temperature (∼1025°C), consistent with its more evolved major element composition (Table 1 and Figure 6a). As expected, the MIs trapped in more primitive olivines (≥Fo88) record higher temperatures (>1150°C) than those trapped in more evolved ones (<1150°C in ≤Fo87), with the exception of the high CaO/Al2O3 MIs. These latter MIs were trapped at the highest pressures (>1.5 kbar) but at the low end of the temperature range (<1150°C), supporting their derivation from a deeper magma storage zone where melt-mush reactions may have taken place [Bédard et al., 2000; Danyushevsky et al., 2004]. No clear relationship exists between pressure and host olivine forsterite content, and so together, the pressure-temperature path of the MIs appears to reflect crystallization during cooling as well as ascent and degassing. The lowest vapor saturation pressures (0.1–0.3 kbar) are recorded in the most degassed MIs (with <1.5 wt % H2O) and in the glass (using H2O of 1.0 wt % from sum deficit and a nominal CO2 content of 50 ppm). These pressures are similar to those expected for the collection depth on the seafloor (∼0.2 kbar for a water depth of ∼1,650 m), indicating that the glass and these MIs were degassing up until eruption [Newman et al., 2000] (Figure 5). This finding illustrates the importance of studying MIs, as opposed to volcanic glasses, in determining preeruptive magmatic volatile contents.

5. High-Ca Boninite Petrogenesis

5.1. Elevated Mantle Temperatures?

[30] Based on laboratory experiments with North Tongan high-Ca boninite compositions, Falloon and Danyushevsky [2000] proposed that high-Ca boninites require temperatures of equilibration as high as 1480°C at depths of ∼45 km (15 kbar) in the mantle. Such temperatures are higher than those estimated beneath most mid-ocean ridges (potential temperature, Tp, of 1400 ± 40°C [Putirka, 2008] or 1300–1400°C [Lee et al., 2009]) and so imply elevated mantle temperature as a condition of high-Ca boninite genesis. Indeed, the high temperatures recorded in the North Tonga boninites, together with the high temperatures characteristic of northern Lau Basin back-arc basalts [Wiens et al., 2006], may be related to infiltration of the hot Samoan plume [Danyushevsky et al., 1995]. Thus, it is worth exploring whether high-Ca boninite magmatism at Volcano A may also be linked to high mantle temperatures.

[31] To evaluate this question, we compare temperatures of primary high-Ca boninite compositions from the North Tonga and Volcano A locations using two different thermobarometers. The first employs the hydrous olivine-liquid thermometer used above [Sugawara, 2000; Médard and Grove, 2008], solved simultaneously with the silica barometer of Albarède [1992]. The second uses a new silica barometer (based on melt-olivine-opx equilibria [Lee et al., 2009]) that improves upon that of Albarède [1992] by including a silica activity model and the effects of H2O. The barometer is solved simultaneously with an olivine-melt thermometer, which includes a silica term to account for the pressure effect [Lee et al., 2009]. For North Tonga, we use the primary melts (Tonga 1 and 2, with MgO of 19 and 24 wt %, respectively) given in Table 4 of Falloon and Danyushevsky [2000], which are based on MIs with 1 to 2 wt % H2O found in Fo93–94 olivines [Sobolev and Danyushevsky, 1994]. For Volcano A, we use the most primitive MI compositions (oliv23-MIa and oliv26-MIa), which are trapped in Fo92 olivines, and the LC-A-4 WR composition, incorporating 4.7 wt % H2O (the maximum measured in any MI) (Table 1). Although the WR is in equilibrium with Fo89 olivine, which is a plausible mantle composition, the presence of Fo92 olivines in the sample suggest equilibration with a more refractory mantle. Thus, we add olivine to the WR composition (assuming Fe3+/ΣFe of 0.2) until it is in equilibrium with Fo92 olivine (requiring 11% addition), yielding 4.2 wt % H2O and 15 wt % MgO in the primary melt.

[32] The high temperatures of the North Tonga high-Ca boninites determined by Falloon and Danyushevsky [2000] are confirmed with the independent thermobarometers of Lee et al. [2009] and of Albarède [1992] and Sugawara [2000], which indicate average melt-mantle equilibration at ∼1490°C and ∼16.5 kbar (Figure 6b). In contrast, the Volcano A high-Ca boninite primary melt compositions reflect lower pressures (∼5–10 kbar) and lower temperatures (∼1175–1285°C) of equilibration, with satisfactory agreement between the two thermobarometers (within their 2–3 kbar and 30–40°C uncertainties) (Table 1). Interestingly, the low pressures of equilibration for Volcano A melts may correspond to Moho pressures (assuming 20–25 km Moho [Crawford et al., 2003]), possibly due to the Moho being a physical barrier to mantle melting, or a rheological boundary that promotes magma ponding and equilibration there. The lower temperatures calculated for Volcano A primary melts are largely due to the lower mantle forsterite assumed (Fo92 versus Fo94) and the higher measured H2O concentrations (>4 versus 1–2 wt %) than in the North Tonga primary melts. The Fo92 composition is based on the maximum found in analyzing ∼40 olivine phenocrysts in sample LC-A-4, most of which were rastered rim-to-rim (Table S1 and Figures 3 and S1). Nevertheless, if we assume Fo94 in the mantle source, then the melt equilibration temperatures for the most primitive Volcano A MIs (16.5 wt % MgO on average) increase ∼100°C, from ∼1200 to ∼1310°C, but are still >100°C cooler than the North Tonga boninites. Moreover, the H2O content of the undegassed Volcano A end-member may be even higher than we have measured, and so these temperatures represent maxima.

[33] We conclude that the lower mantle melting temperatures calculated for high-Ca boninites from Volcano A (<1300°C) are robust, and note the similarity to those calculated for other arc volcanoes and back-arc spreading centers [Elkins Tanton et al., 2001; Leeman et al., 2005; Currie and Hyndman, 2006; Wiens et al., 2006; Rychert et al., 2008]. Given the typical mantle melting temperatures, it is unlikely that the Volcano A mantle source has been thermally affected by the Samoan plume. This is supported by isotopic analyses of Lau Basin back-arc basalts which suggest that the southern extent of the Samoan plume is at ∼17°S, ∼400 km north of Volcano A (Figure 1b) [Volpe et al., 1988; Pearce et al., 1994]. In addition, these low temperatures are consistent with the absence of a positive Zr anomaly in the Volcano A WRs, which could indicate high temperatures needed to melt amphibolites in the slab [Bédard, 1999] (Figure 4b). Based on these observations, we exclude anomalously high mantle temperatures as a primary cause of high-Ca boninite petrogenesis at Volcano A, and by extension, as a general requirement for high-Ca boninite petrogenesis. These findings, allied with older studies [Tatsumi, 1981; Umino and Kushiro, 1989; van der Laan et al., 1989; Kushiro, 1990], suggest that boninite formation may occur over a range of pressure and temperature conditions, anywhere from <10 to 25 kbar and 1000 to ∼1500°C.

5.2. Hydrous Fluid Addition?

[34] Previous work indicates that extensive melting of the mantle generates primary boninite liquids in equilibrium with harzburgite [Crawford et al., 1989]. Such a scenario requires either temperatures in the mantle wedge far in excess of the peridotite solidus, or hydrous fluid addition to lower the solidus. Because high mantle wedge temperatures do not appear to be a factor for high-Ca boninite generation at Volcano A, the addition of a hydrous fluid is required. Such fluid fluxing is supported by the LILE enrichments with respect to REEs and HFSEs observed in the trace element patterns of high-Ca boninites from Volcano A (Figure 4b) and low-Ca boninites from Betts Cove Ophiolite [Bédard, 1999]. H2O contents in the primary high-Ca boninite liquid at Volcano A (>4 wt %) are higher than those estimated for other primary boninite liquids (1–3 wt %) [Newman and van der Laan, 1992; Ohnenstetter and Brown, 1996; Sobolev and Chaussidon, 1996; Falloon and Danyushevsky, 2000]. It is important to point out, however, that these concentrations are not unusually high when compared with many arc magmas [Wallace, 2005]. Thus, H2O may be a necessary, but not sufficient, condition for boninite genesis.

5.3. Melting of a Refractory (cpx-Poor) Source?

[35] Progressive partial melting of a peridotite mantle source is characterized by cpx exhaustion from lherzolite, followed by opx exhaustion from harzburgite. During dry conditions, as modal cpx decreases, the residual liquid composition continuously decreases in SiO2 and TiO2 as MgO increases [Kinzler and Grove, 1992, 1993]. After cpx exhaustion, however, as modal opx decreases, the liquid composition continuously increases in SiO2 as MgO increases and TiO2 decreases [Falloon and Danyushevsky, 2000; Parman and Grove, 2004; Wood and Turner, 2009]. This compositional vector is the one that corresponds to boninites, and so, most petrogenetic models for boninite generation appeal to harzburgite-liquid equilibrium. It has also long been argued that H2O increases the SiO2 content of mantle melts, due to its interaction with silica chains in the melt [Kushiro, 1972], and yet, peridotite melting experiments show this effect to be subtle at best [e.g., Gaetani and Grove, 1998; Parman and Grove, 2004; Grove et al., 2006]. Instead, another driver of high SiO2 contents in wet melts is the common practice of reporting analyses on an anhydrous basis; 5 wt % H2O can make a boninite (52.5 wt % SiO2) from a basalt (50 wt % SiO2) simply from the renormalization process. The final factor affecting the SiO2 content of primary melts is the pressure of melting, where low pressures generate higher SiO2 melts, due in part to the large volume change on the reaction olivine + SiO2(liq) → opx. Thus, from these principles, we would expect primary boninite liquids to be generated at shallow depths in the mantle, have high H2O contents, and be in equilibrium with harzburgite.

[36] In sections 5.1 and 5.2, we have shown that the primary high-Ca boninite liquids from Volcano A have equilibrated at shallow depths (∼5–10 kbar) and have high H2O contents (>4 wt %). To understand whether the primary liquids are in equilibrium with harzburgite, we performed the following test. Assuming batch melting, an initial TiO2 concentration of 0.133 wt %, consistent with an average depleted mantle composition, and a bulk partition coefficient for TiO2 of 0.04, we calculated 39% total partial melting of a fertile mantle source to generate Volcano A high-Ca boninite primary liquids [Salters and Stracke, 2004; Kelley et al., 2006]. This single melting episode is consistent with the depleted REE patterns of the Volcano A WRs and indicates cpx exhaustion within the peridotite residue [Baker and Stolper, 1994]. Alternatively, high-Ca boninites at Volcano A could also be generated by two episodes of melting from an originally fertile source: one to generate cpx-poor lherzolite in the back arc (F1) and the other to generate high-Ca boninites in the arc (F2), summing to a total melt depletion of ∼39%.

[37] Although single stage and double stage melting may produce melts with similar major element compositions [Parman and Grove, 2004], they reflect very different physical processes. In the context of the Volcano A high-Ca boninites, the single stage model would involve very large degrees of melting beneath the arc (yielding significant melt volumes) due to a very large H2O input from the subducting slab. In the two-stage model, prior melting would occur in the back-arc melting regime (mostly dry), and the mantle would melt again (wet) beneath the arc but with lower H2O in the source and yielding smaller melt volumes than in the single stage model. Thus, Volcano A high-Ca boninites could derive either from exceptionally high H2O contents in the mantle source or from extensive prior melting in the Lau Basin.

[38] It is difficult to exclude the possibility of extremely high H2O contents in the Volcano A mantle source as a means to produce high-Ca boninites, as extremely high degrees of melting could lower the H2O contents in the melt to the observed concentrations, which are typical of average arc magmas. Yet there is no a priori reason why the H2O flux from the subducting slab would be greater here than elsewhere along the arc. On the other hand, the nearby Lau back-arc basin provides a ready means of melting mantle that may melt again under the arc. Such a scenario may explain the depleted REE patterns of Tonga Arc magmas, without massive extents of melting beneath the arc. This process, called preconditioning, has been previously described and modeled by McCulloch and Gamble [1991], Woodhead et al. [1993], Kincaid and Hall [2003], and Pearce [2005] as a means to generate high field strength (incompatible) element depletions in arc magmas. We suggest that the generation of arc high-Ca boninites at Volcano A may occur if significant preconditioning in the back arc is followed by further melting in the arc melting regime. But why would high-Ca boninites only occur at Volcano A, given that back-arc spreading centers occur almost continuously along the arc? To answer this question, we next consider whether other Tonga Arc magmas might have a high-Ca boninite parentage, and then propose an arc–back-arc evolutionary model that predicts the spatial occurrence of boninites along the Tonga Arc.

5.4. A Boninitic Heritage for Other Tonga Arc Volcanoes?

[39] The simple genetic relationship for all samples dredged from Volcano A (Figures 2 and 4) suggests a common high-Ca boninite parent for the entire Volcano A complex, even if high-Ca boninites (in the strict sense) are only erupted at one locale. What we interpret as evolved high-Ca boninites at Volcano A represent a fairly common composition erupted in this region of the Tonga Arc. This raises the possibility that previously described basaltic andesites in the Tonga Arc have also evolved from high-Ca boninite parents.

[40] In order to assess the heritage of magmas erupted from other Tonga Arc volcanoes, we have examined their Si-Mg-Ti relationships. The hallmark of a primary boninite (either high Ca or low Ca) is its anomalously high SiO2 and low TiO2. This will translate into evolved magmas with high SiO2 and low TiO2 at a given MgO, which can be quantified using Si6.0 and Ti6.0 (i.e., SiO2 and TiO2 concentrations at MgO of 6 wt % [Plank and Langmuir, 1988]). We thus consider the combination of high Si6.0 (>53 wt %) and low Ti6.0 (<0.65 wt %) to reflect a boninitic heritage, and the combination of low Si6.0 and high Ti6.0 to reflect a basaltic heritage. Alternatively, low Si6.0 and low Ti6.0 would reflect an intermediate incompatible element-depleted basaltic heritage (see section 6), and high Si6.0 and high Ti6.0 would reflect a possible slab melt input. The above magmatic heritage cutoff lines (at 53 wt % Si6.0 and 0.65 wt % Ti6.0) were determined by projecting the full range of compositions within the IUGS boninite field of Le Bas [2000] to 6 wt % MgO along olivine control lines (see Figures 2, 7, and 8a). These discriminants permit an evaluation of boninite parentage in volcanic suites that are otherwise too evolved to be classed as true boninites (i.e., MgO < 8 wt %).

[41] To test the accuracy of this magmatic heritage classification scheme, we calculated Si6.0 and Ti6.0 for 7 classic boninitic suites (both high Ca and low Ca) and ∼175 global active arc volcanoes (see Figure 7 for details). Figure 7 shows that while the magmatic heritage of arc volcanoes is variable, though predominantly basaltic, all of the boninitic suites fall within the boninitic heritage field. In addition, we observe a correlation between melt composition and tectonic setting. Arc volcanoes with adjacent back-arc basins have the lowest Ti6.0 (i.e., greatest mantle depletion and highest degree of melting), while those with no back-arc basins have moderate Ti6.0, and continental arc volcanoes have the highest Ti6.0 (i.e., least mantle depletion and lowest degree of melting). Only arc volcanoes with back-arc basins have the low Ti6.0 required for a boninitic heritage. Thus, this simple magmatic heritage scheme accurately predicts a boninitic heritage for known boninitic suites, and suggests that other arc volcanoes that develop adjacent to back arcs might also have a boninitic heritage.

[42] Tonga submarine and subaerial volcanoes vary greatly in their magmatic heritage along the strike of the arc (Figures 8a and 8b). In the south, the volcanoes located adjacent to the nascent Southern Lau Rift and Valu Fa Ridge (volcanoes 19, 18, 7, and Ata) have a basaltic heritage, with low Si6.0 and high Ti6.0. In the middle of the arc, the volcanoes located adjacent to the more established Lau spreading centers (i.e., the ELSC, Intermediate Lau Spreading Center (ILSC), and Central Lau Spreading Center (CLSC)) (volcanoes 1, A, Tofua, Metis Shoal, Late, and F) have a boninitic heritage. Farther north, where the tectonic setting is more complex, Niuatoputapu and Tafahi have a boninitic and incompatible element-depleted basaltic heritage, respectively. Thus, we do not consider the boninitic heritage of Volcano A to be an isolated occurrence, but to characterize several other volcanoes, particularly those in the central region of the active Tonga Arc. This view is consistent with the unusually low 231Pa/235U activity ratios observed in the central portion of the Tonga Arc (volcanoes Hunga, Tofua, Late, and Fonualei [Bourdon et al., 1999]), interpreted by Bourdon et al. [1999] as requiring the near absence of cpx in the initial sub-arc melting mode. Such an interpretation is entirely consistent with the inferences here: that unusually refractory mantle with low modal cpx generates high-Ca boninite parental melts that source many of the volcanoes in this region of the Tonga Arc. This interpretation differs, however, from that recently presented by Caulfield et al. [2008], based on high field strength depletions observed in Tonga magmas. They propose very small degrees of prior melting in the back arc (<1%), which would decrease the cpx mode only minimally, followed by large (>25%) melting in the arc. Reconciliation of major element, trace element, and isotope systematics is a topic of future efforts.

6. Conceptual Arc–Back-Arc Evolutionary Model

[43] In an early model by Crawford et al. [1981], distinct pulses of boninite generation were explained by multiple episodes of back-arc initiation. Ascending diapirs beneath the arc axis caused arc magmatism to cease, and partial melting of the diapirs yielded first limited boninite and then voluminous mid-ocean ridge basalt tholeiite magmatism, which caused the arc to split in half. While this model has been subsequently superseded in favor of subduction zone initiation [Pearce et al., 1992; Stern and Bloomer, 1992] or thermal anomalies due to mantle plumes [Macpherson and Hall, 2001], it serves as a precedent for explaining boninite generation within the temporal evolution of an arc–back-arc system.

[44] Here we explore how arc boninites (either low Ca or high Ca) may be generated within the large-scale mantle flow of an evolving arc–back-arc system, and use high-Ca boninite generation in the Tonga-Lau system as an example (Figure 8c). In this conceptual model, mantle flow lines intersect the back-arc melting regime (triangular region in Figure 8c), inducing melting of a fertile source (F1). The residual peridotite is entrained by corner flow into the mantle wedge, and the addition of slab-derived hydrous fluid promotes additional melting (F2) in the arc melting regime (circular region in the mantle wedge in Figure 8c). The primary factor contributing to the generation of primary liquids with different compositions is the fertility of the peridotite source in the arc melting regime. When the source is fertile, primary basalts are generated; when the source is residual with low F1, primary incompatible element-depleted basalts are generated. Boninite primary liquids are generated when the source is residual with high F1 (i.e., containing low modal cpx). This is consistent with the TiO2 limit in the boninite definition of Le Bas [2000], since <0.5 wt % TiO2 would reflect >24% total partial melting of a fertile source (given the same initial concentration and partition coefficient of TiO2 as in section 5.3), which is indicative of cpx exhaustion [Baker and Stolper, 1994].

[45] The key to making boninites in this way is to bring mantle that has melted in the back-arc melting regime into the arc melting regime. This requires an additional component of horizontal flow, for if residual peridotite flows at the same rate as back-arc crust formation (equal to the half spreading rate, USR), it will never reach the arc melting regime. Instead, subduction adds an extra component of flow, related to the “corner flow rate” (UCF), a fraction of the convergence rate (UCR) (Figure 8c). Near the subducting slab-mantle wedge boundary, UCF is equal to UCR; farther within the mantle wedge, UCF decreases due to a decrease in the viscous coupling with the slab. When back-arc spreading begins, the residual peridotite is confined to the incipient back-arc melting regime, at a distance Δxi from the arc (i.e., the initial separation distance between the arc and back-arc spreading center). Subduction-driven corner flow causes the back-arc mantle to flow faster than the back-arc spreading rate (i.e., USR + UCF), and with time (t), residual peridotite will travel some distance ahead of the back-arc crustal accretion zone (ΔxCF), where ΔxCF = UCF * t. When ΔxCF ≥ Δxi, refractory mantle (i.e., low modal cpx) has reached the arc melting regime, and incompatible element-depleted basalt or boninite primary liquids may be formed.

[46] For a given volcano located adjacent to an active back-arc spreading center, the following sequence will develop with time, provided USR, UCF, and Δxi remain constant (Figure 8c). Initially, when there is no back-arc spreading center, primary basalts form in the arc melting regime from fertile peridotite (stage I). After the initiation of back-arc spreading but when ΔxCF < Δxi, refractory peridotite from the back-arc melting regime has not yet reached the arc melting regime, and primary basalts will still form beneath the arc (stages II and III). Later, when ΔxCF = Δxi, the first residual peridotite will have arrived at the arc melting regime (stage IV); it is likely derived from the deeper, more distal parts of the back-arc melting regime, which have experienced lower F1 [Plank and Langmuir, 1992]. This mantle will generate basalts that are depleted in incompatible elements, but are not boninites, because this mantle has not yet experienced enough cumulative melting (>∼24%). When ΔxCF > Δxi, residual peridotite which has experienced greater F1 will enter the arc melting regime and potentially generate boninites (stage V).

[47] This arc–back-arc model predicts that a single volcano may evolve over time, first erupting basalts, then incompatible element-depleted basalts, and ultimately boninites (Figure 8c). We can also imagine a later time when the large distance between the arc and back-arc melting regimes may lead to an absence of refractory peridotite in the arc melting regime and normal basalts may be generated once again (stage VI). Similarly, if USR is too fast, UCR is too slow, or Δxi is too large, fertile peridotite may be entrained into the mantle wedge before residual mantle makes it to the arc, and stages IV and V may never be reached. It is also likely that UCF will vary within the mantle wedge, as outlined above, with higher rates in the upper portions of the back-arc melting regime. If this is the case, the first residual peridotite to enter the arc melting regime will have experienced high F1, and boninites may be generated earlier in the sequence. Last, the sequence will vary if the rates evolve over time, or if flow is more complex than the idealized corner flow [cf. Kincaid and Hall, 2003].

[48] In the Tonga-Lau system, where the volcanic arc is located adjacent to a southward propagating back-arc spreading center, it is possible to use this arc–back-arc evolutionary model to describe not only the variations expected in a single volcano over time but also those along the entire arc within the current snapshot (Figure 8). We expect different parts of the arc to be in different evolutionary stages. For example, in the south, where the active ridge has yet to propagate (i.e., the Southern Lau Rift), we would expect the arc to be in stage I. Indeed, volcanoes 19 and 18 reflect a basaltic heritage. Moving north, the arc adjacent to incipient spreading at the Valu Fa Ridge should be in stage II/III, and this is also consistent with the basaltic heritage of Volcano 7 and Ata. The central volcanoes of the Tonga Arc (volcanoes 1, A, Tofua, Metis Shoal, Late, and F) may owe their boninitic heritage to stage V conditions, where enough time has elapsed for residual mantle from the more long-lived spreading centers (i.e., the ELSC, ILSC, and CLSC) to reach the arc melting regime and melt again. An interesting prediction is that volcanism between Ata and Volcano 1 may represent stage IV, and we might expect incompatible element-depleted basalts or their derivatives to be found there in the future. Because of the tectonic complexity and paucity of young arc volcanism in the northern Tonga Arc, due in part to the nascent Fonulaei Spreading Center having captured all the volcanism [Keller et al., 2008], we cannot properly assess the evolutionary stages reflected in Tafahi and Niuatoputapu magmas.

[49] We can also use the evolutionary melting model to estimate the average UCF for mantle flow lines intersecting the arc melting regime at Volcano A. Approximately 30 km of new back-arc crust has been generated in ∼0.8 Ma at the latitude of Volcano A, where Δxi is ∼45 km [Zellmer and Taylor, 2001]. Because high-Ca boninites erupt at Volcano A, ΔxCF > Δxi, and so UCF is >55 km/Myr (i.e., 45/0.8). This corner flow rate is approximately one third of the full convergence rate at this latitude (∼165 km/Myr [Bevis et al., 1995]), and provides a potentially useful constraint for future geodynamic models, specifically those that try to relate plate kinematics to mantle flow. Interestingly, our results are entirely consistent with work by Kincaid and Griffiths [2004], who estimate velocities in the mantle wedge to be 30 to 40% of the downdip plate speed for longitudinal slab sinking without slab rollback. As UCF is a function of UCR, and because UCR increases dramatically from 70 to 240 km/Myr from south to north along the strike of the Tonga Arc [Bevis et al., 1995], we predict that the average UCF for mantle flow lines intersecting the arc melting regime will vary between ∼20 and 70 km/Myr along strike. However, this will be accurate only if that the relationship between UCR and the average UCF for the entire Tonga Arc is similar to Volcano A. Furthermore, we predict that the time required to generate high-Ca boninites in the arc after back-arc initiation will decrease significantly from south to north, from ∼2 to 0.5 Ma. This is contingent on the notions that primary boninite generation is ultimately related to ΔxCF/Δxi (which determines whether residual peridotite from the back arc will be entrained into the arc melting regime) and that Δxi is relatively constant along the entire arc.

[50] The average UCF estimated here for the northern Tonga Arc (∼70 km/Myr) can be compared to that estimated by Turner and Hawkesworth [1997], based on the appearance of what they interpreted as Louisville Pb in Tafahi and Niuatoputapu volcanoes. Because the Louisville Ridge subducted into this region of the arc 2 to 4 Ma ago, they argue that wedge overturn rates must be slow (no more than 20–40 km/Myr) to delay the arrival of Louisville Pb into the arc melting regime. An alternative source of the Pb has recently been proposed by Falloon et al. [2007], in the form of more proximal Cook-Austral type Pb, as found in some seamounts near Samoa. The more recent subduction of these proximal volcaniclastics would allow faster wedge overturn rates, more consistent with those predicted here.

7. Conclusions

[51] Volcano A in the Tonga volcanic arc is the first known high-Ca boninite volcano from an active arc. This discovery demonstrates that unusual tectonic settings may not be necessary to generate high-Ca boninites, but special conditions are. The key requirement for boninite generation is high cumulative degrees of melting (>∼24%) of refractory mantle peridotite (i.e., low modal cpx), such that final melts are in equilibrium with harzburgite (olivine + opx). Such a process can happen in multiple stages, but the final one must occur with high resulting H2O contents in the melt (2–5 wt %), leading to primary melts with high SiO2 concentration (on an anhydrous basis). The pressure and temperature of melting is less pertinent to the creation of high-Ca boninites than wet melting with final melts in equilibrium with harzburgite. We propose a conceptual two-stage melting model for arc high-Ca boninite petrogenesis at Volcano A: (1) melting of a fertile peridotite within the Lau back-arc melting regime, (2) followed by remelting of this peridotite with slab-derived fluid beneath the Tonga Arc. There is a geodynamic control on this process, whereby subduction-driven corner flow brings residual peridotite from the back-arc melting regime into the arc mantle wedge. Such a process at Volcano A would require corner flow rates at a significant fraction (>30%) of the convergence rate. Mantle remelting occurs to various extents along the Tonga Arc, but is best developed in its central portion (18–21°S), where we believe not only Volcano A, but several nearby volcanoes, are sourced by high-Ca boninite primary melts. A simple way to identify boninite parentage is by unusually high Si6.0 and low Ti6.0 (and low 231Pa/235U activities); this scheme implicates high-Ca boninite parents in volcanic rocks that would otherwise be classified as basaltic andesites.

[52] High-Ca boninite magmatism within the modern Tonga Arc has implications for both the present and past. Some of the boninites described in the geological record may not have formed in a fore arc or back arc or during arc initiation, as is commonly inferred, but instead they may have formed within the confines of a normal volcanic arc. By analogy to the Tonga-Lau system, however, such arc boninites might require a concurrently active back-arc spreading center, and so the recognition of such arc boninites may point to specific plate configurations. It is also possible that other active arc volcanoes erupt magmas of boninitic heritage that have not yet been recognized. Using the Si6.0 and Ti6.0 discriminants developed here, a few active volcanoes in the New Britain and Papua New Guinea and Vanuatu arcs are potentially derived from primary boninite liquids (Figure 7). Back-arc spreading in the Manus and North Fiji basins may have preconditioned mantle for arc boninite generation in a manner parallel to that proposed here for the Tonga-Lau system.
